<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Origin_stories">Origin stor=
ies</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DChinese_=
zodiac&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Origin sto=
ries"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<p>Many <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narrative" title=3D"Narrat=
ive">stories</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fable" title=
=3D"Fable">fables</a> explain the beginning of the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Zodiac" title=3D"Zodiac">zodiac</a>. Since the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Han_dynasty" title=3D"Han dynasty">Han dynast=
y</a>, the twelve <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earthly_Branches=
" title=3D"Earthly Branches">Earthly Branches</a> have been used to record =
the time of day. However, for entertainment and convenience,<sup class=3D"n=
oprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"W=
ikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to rel=
iable sources. (December 2020)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> they =
were replaced by the twelve animals, and a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Mnemonic" title=3D"Mnemonic">mnemonic</a> refers to the behavior o=
f the animals:
</p><p>Earthly Branches may refer to a double-hour period.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese=
_zodiac#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the latter case it is the center of th=
e period; for instance, =E9=A6=AC m=C7=8E (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Horse_(zodiac)" title=3D"Horse (zodiac)">Horse</a>) means noon as =
well as a period from 11:00 to 13:00.
</p>
