<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Rat_and_Ox.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"=
><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/78/Rat_=
and_Ox.jpg/250px-Rat_and_Ox.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D=
"196" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2838" data-file-height=
=3D"2230"></a><figcaption>This image depicts a scene from "The Great Race" =
folk story, in which the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ox_(zodia=
c)" title=3D"Ox (zodiac)">Ox</a> carries the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Rat_(zodiac)" title=3D"Rat (zodiac)">Rat</a> across the river.</=
figcaption></figure>
<p>An ancient <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Folklore" title=3D"F=
olklore">folktale</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> cal=
led "The Great Race" tells of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Jade_Emperor" title=3D"Jade Emperor">Jade Emperor</a>'s decree that the yea=
rs on the calendar would be named for each animal in the order they reached=
 him. To get there, the animals would have to cross a river.
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote">
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cat_(zodiac)" title=3D"Cat =
(zodiac)">Cat</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rat_(zod=
iac)" title=3D"Rat (zodiac)">Rat</a> were not good at swimming, but they we=
re both quite intelligent. They decided that the best and fastest way to cr=
oss the river was to hop on the back of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Ox_(zodiac)" title=3D"Ox (zodiac)">Ox</a>. The Ox, being kindhear=
ted and naive, agreed to carry them both across. As the Ox was about to rea=
ch the other side of the river, the Rat pushed the Cat into the water, and =
then jumped off the Ox and rushed to the Jade Emperor. It was named as the =
first animal of the zodiac calendar. The Ox had to settle for second place.
</p><p>The third animal to come was the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Tiger_(zodiac)" title=3D"Tiger (zodiac)">Tiger</a>. Even though it wa=
s strong and powerful, it admitted to the Jade Emperor that the currents we=
re pushing it downstream.
</p><p>Suddenly, a <i>thump</i> sound came from the distance, signaling the=
 arrival of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rabbit_(zodiac)" t=
itle=3D"Rabbit (zodiac)">Rabbit</a>. It explained how it crossed the river:=
 by jumping from one stone to another in a nimble fashion. Halfway through,=
 it thought it might lose the race, but it was lucky enough to grab hold of=
 a floating log that later washed it to shore. For that, it became the four=
th animal in the zodiac cycle.
</p><p>In fifth place was the flying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Dragon_(zodiac)" title=3D"Dragon (zodiac)">Dragon</a>. The Jade Emperor =
wondered why a swift, airborne creature such as the Dragon did not come in =
first place. The Dragon explained that it had to stop by a village and brin=
g rain for all the people, and therefore it was held back. Then, on its way=
 to the finish, it saw the helpless Rabbit clinging onto a log, so it did a=
 good deed and gave a puff of breath in the poor creature's direction so th=
at it could land on the shore. The Jade Emperor was astonished by the Drago=
n's good nature, and it was named as the fifth animal of the zodiac.
</p><p>As soon as the Dragon arrived, there came a galloping sound, and the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horse_(zodiac)" title=3D"Horse (z=
odiac)">Horse</a> appeared. Hidden on the Horse's hoof was the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Snake_(zodiac)" title=3D"Snake (zodiac)">Snake=
</a>, whose sudden appearance gave the Horse a fright, thus making it fall =
back and giving the Snake the sixth spot while the Horse placed seventh.
</p><p>After a while, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goat_(zo=
diac)" title=3D"Goat (zodiac)">Goat</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Monkey_(zodiac)" title=3D"Monkey (zodiac)">Monkey</a>, and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rooster_(zodiac)" title=3D"Rooster (zodia=
c)">Rooster</a> came to the river blocking the heavenly gate. The Rooster f=
ound a raft, and the Monkey and the Goat tugged and pulled, trying to get a=
ll the weeds out of the way. With combined efforts, they managed to arrive =
to the other side. The Jade Emperor was pleased with their teamwork and dec=
ided to name the Goat as the eighth animal, followed by the Monkey and then=
 the Rooster.
</p><p>The eleventh animal placed in the zodiac cycle was the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dog_(zodiac)" title=3D"Dog (zodiac)">Dog</a>. A=
lthough it should have been the best swimmer and runner, it spent its time =
playing in the river water. Its explanation for being late was that it need=
ed a good bath after a long journey, but it almost did not make it to the f=
inish line.
</p><p>Right when the Jade Emperor was going to end the race, an <i>oink</i=
> sound was heard: it was the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pig_=
(zodiac)" title=3D"Pig (zodiac)">Pig</a>. The Pig felt hungry in the middle=
 of the race, so it stopped, ate something, and then fell asleep. After it =
awoke, it finished the race in twelfth place, making it the last animal to =
arrive.
</p><p>
The Cat eventually drowned and failed to become part of the zodiac. It is s=
aid that this is the reason why cats hate water. It is also the reason for =
the rivalry between the Cat and Rat, as it was the Rat's callous act to pus=
h the Cat into the river.</p></blockquote>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Variations">Variations</h4>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DChinese_zodiac&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Variations"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Another version of the folktale tells that the Rat deceived the Ox into =
letting it jump on its back by promising the Ox that it could hear the Rat =
sing,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CyndiChen_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-CyndiChen-28"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> before jumping off at the finish line and finishing first. Another varia=
nt says that the Rat cheated the Cat out its place at the finish line, by h=
iding on the back of the Dog, who was too focused to notice that he had a s=
tow-away. The Cat tried to attack the rat in retaliation, but hurt the Dog =
by accident. This is said to account for the antagonistic dynamic between c=
ats and rats, beyond normal predator and prey behavior, and also why dogs a=
nd cats fight.
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_mythology" title=
=3D"Chinese mythology">Chinese mythology</a>, a story tells that the cat wa=
s tricked by the Rat so it could not go to the banquet. This is why the Cat=
 is ultimately not part of the Chinese zodiac.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-=
Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citat=
ion needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources.=
 (June 2019)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_Buddhism" title=
=3D"Chinese Buddhism">Buddhist</a> legend <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Gautama_Buddha" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gautama Buddha">Gaut=
ama Buddha</a> summoned all animals of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Earth_(Wu_Xing)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Earth (Wu Xing)">E=
arth</a> to come before him before his departure from this <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth_(Wu_Xing)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ea=
rth (Wu Xing)">Earth</a>, but only twelve animals came to bid him farewell.=
 To reward these animals, he named a year after each of them in the order t=
hey had arrived.
</p><p>The twelve animals of the Chinese zodiac were developed in the early=
 stages of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_China" title=
=3D"History of China">Chinese civilization</a>, so therefore it is difficul=
t to investigate its real origins. Most historians agree that the Cat is no=
t included, as cats had not yet been introduced to China from India with th=
e arrival of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddhism" title=3D"Bu=
ddhism">Buddhism</a>. However until recently, the Vietnamese moved away fro=
m their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Traditional_Vietnamese_med=
icine" title=3D"Traditional Vietnamese medicine">traditional texts</a><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and literature and, unlike al=
l other countries who follow the Sino lunar calendar, include the Cat inste=
ad of the Rabbit as a zodiac animal. The most common explanation is that ca=
ts are worshipped by farmers in East Asia, believing that cats' luck and pr=
osperity protects their crops.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-30"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> Another popular cultural reason is that the ancient word for <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rabbit_(zodiac)" title=3D"Rabbit (zodiac)=
">rabbit</a> (Mao) sounds like cat (Meo).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note=
-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Adaptations">Adaptations</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
