ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal" tit=
le=3D"Help:Maintenance template removal">Learn how and when to remove this =
message</a></small>)</i></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>The Chinese zodiac signs are also used by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Chinese_culture" title=3D"Chinese culture">cultures</a> other th=
an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_language" title=3D"Chin=
ese language">Chinese</a>. For example, they usually appear on <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Korean_New_Year" title=3D"Korean New Year">Kor=
ean New Year</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_New_=
Year" title=3D"Japanese New Year">Japanese New Year</a>'s cards and stamps.=
 The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Postal_Service"=
 title=3D"United States Postal Service">United States Postal Service</a> an=
d several other countries' postal services issue a "Year of the ____" posta=
ge stamp each year to honor this <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
hinese_language" title=3D"Chinese language">Chinese</a> <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_China" title=3D"History of China">heritage=
</a>.
</p><p>The zodiac is widely used in commercial culture, for example, in the=
 Chinese New Year market, and popular zodiac-related products, such as craf=
ts, toys, books, accessories, and paintings and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Chinese_lunar_coins" title=3D"Chinese lunar coins">Chinese lu=
nar coins</a>. The coins depict <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zo=
diac" title=3D"Zodiac">zodiac</a> animals, inspired the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canadian_Silver_Maple_Leaf#Privy_Mark_Silver_Maple_Le=
af" title=3D"Canadian Silver Maple Leaf">Canadian Silver Maple Leaf</a> <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coin" title=3D"Coin">coins</a>, as we=
ll as varieties from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australia" ti=
tle=3D"Australia">Australia</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
outh_Korea" title=3D"South Korea">South Korea</a>, and <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mongolia" title=3D"Mongolia">Mongolia</a>.
</p><p>The Chinese zodiac is also used in some Asian countries that were un=
der the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_culture" title=3D"=
Chinese culture">cultural</a> influence of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/China" title=3D"China">China</a>. However, some of the animals in =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zodiac" title=3D"Zodiac">zodia=
c</a> may differ by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Country" title=
=3D"Country">country</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Asian">Asian <span class=3D=
"anchor" id=3D"korean"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"vietnamese"></sp=
an></h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DChinese_=
zodiac&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Asian"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bulgar_calend=
ar" title=3D"Bulgar calendar">Bulgar calendar</a> and <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vietnamese_zodiac" title=3D"Vietnamese zodiac">Vietname=
se zodiac</a></div>
<p>The <b>Korean zodiac</b> includes the <i>Sheep</i> (<i>yang</i>) instead=
 of the <i>Goat</i> (which would be <i>yeomso</i>), although the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_language" title=3D"Chinese language"=
>Chinese</a> source of the loanword <i>yang</i> may refer to any <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caprinae" title=3D"Caprinae">goat-antelope</=
a>.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-spac=
e:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_=
needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs=
 references to reliable sources. (January 2022)">citation needed</span></a>=
</i>]</sup>
</p><p>The <b>Japanese zodiac</b> includes the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Sheep" title=3D"Sheep">Sheep</a></i> (<i>hitsuji</i>) inste=
ad of the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goat_(zodiac)" title=
=3D"Goat (zodiac)">Goat</a></i> (which would be <i>yagi</i>), and the <i><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wild_boar" title=3D"Wild boar">Wild =
boar</a></i> (<i>inoshishi</i>, <i>i</i>) instead of the <i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pig_(zodiac)" title=3D"Pig (zodiac)">Pig</a></i> =
(<i>buta</i>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Since 1873=
, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_people" title=3D"Ja=
panese people">Japanese</a> have celebrated the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Japanese_New_Year" title=3D"Japanese New Year">Japanese New Y=
ear</a> on 1 January as per the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gr=
egorian_calendar" title=3D"Gregorian calendar">Gregorian calendar</a>.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <b>Vietnamese zodiac</b> varies from the Chinese zodiac with the=
 second animal being the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Water_buf=
falo_(zodiac)" title=3D"Water buffalo (zodiac)">Water Buffalo</a> instead o=
f the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ox_(zodiac)" title=3D"Ox (zo=
diac)">Ox</a>, and the fourth animal being the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Cat_(zodiac)" title=3D"Cat (zodiac)">Cat</a> instead of the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rabbit_(zodiac)" title=3D"Rabbit (zo=
diac)">Rabbit</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <b>Cambodian zodiac</b> is exactly identical to that of the Chin=
ese although the dragon is interchangeable with the Neak (<a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N%C4%81ga" title=3D"N=C4=81ga">n=C4=81ga</a>) <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cambodia" title=3D"Cambodia">Cambodian<=
/a> sea snake.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Sheep and =
Goat are interchangeable as well. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Cambodian_New_Year" title=3D"Cambodian New Year">Cambodian New Year</a>=
 is celebrated in April, rather than in January or February as it is in Chi=
na and most countries.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-36"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cham_calendar" title=
=3D"Cham calendar">Cham zodiac</a></b> uses the same order as the Chinese z=
odiac, but replaces the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monkey_(zo=
diac)" title=3D"Monkey (zodiac)">Monkey</a> with the turtle (known locally =
as <i>kra</i>).
</p><p>Similarly the <b>Malay zodiac</b> replaces the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rabbit_(zodiac)" title=3D"Rabbit (zodiac)">Rabbit</a> w=
ith the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chevrotain" title=3D"Chevr=
otain">mousedeer</a> (<i>pelanduk</i>) and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Pig_(zodiac)" title=3D"Pig (zodiac)">Pig</a> with the tortoise=
 (<i>kura</i> or <i>kura-kura</i>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-38"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dragon_(zodiac)" ti=
tle=3D"Dragon (zodiac)">Dragon</a> (<i>Loong</i>) is normally equated with =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N%C4%81ga" title=3D"N=C4=81ga"=
>n=C4=81ga</a> but it is sometimes called Big Snake (<i>ular besar</i>) whi=
le the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Snake_(zodiac)" title=3D"Sn=
ake (zodiac)">Snake sign</a> is called Second Snake (<i>ular sani</i>). Thi=
s is also recorded in a 19th-century manuscript compiled by <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Leyden" title=3D"John Leyden">John Leyden</a=
>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <b>Thai zodiac</b> includes a <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/N%C4%81ga" title=3D"N=C4=81ga">n=C4=81ga</a></i> in place of the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dragon_(zodiac)" title=3D"Dragon (=
zodiac)">Dragon</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-40"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and b=
egins, not at the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_New_Year=
" title=3D"Chinese New Year">Chinese New Year</a>, but either on the first =
day of the fifth month in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thai=
_lunar_calendar" title=3D"Thai lunar calendar">Thai lunar calendar</a>, or =
during the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Songkran_(Thailand)" ti=
tle=3D"Songkran (Thailand)">Songkran</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Songkran" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Songkran">New Year festival=
</a> (now celebrated every 13=E2=80=9315 April), depending on the purpose o=
f the use.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Historically, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lan_Na" title=3D"Lan=
 Na">Lan Na</a> (Kingdom around Northern Thailand) also replaces pig with e=
lephant. While modern Thai have returned to pig, its name is still <a href=
=3D"https://th.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%B8%E0%B8%99" class=3D"ext=
iw" title=3D"th:=E0=B8=81=E0=B8=B8=E0=B8=99">=E0=B8=81=E0=B8=B8=E0=B8=99 (g=
u=CC=9Cn)</a>, retaining the actual word for elephant in the zodiac.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gurung_people" title=
=3D"Gurung people">Gurung</a> zodiac</b> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Nepal" title=3D"Nepal">Nepal</a> includes a Cow instead of an Ox,=
 a Cat instead of Rabbit, an Eagle instead of a Dragon (<i>Loong</i>), a Bi=
rd instead of a Rooster, and a Deer instead of a Pig.<sup class=3D"noprint =
Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedi=
a:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable s=
ources. (January 2022)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>The <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bulgar_calendar" tit=
le=3D"Bulgar calendar">Bulgar calendar</a></b> used from the 2nd century<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and that has been only part=
ially reconstructed uses a similar sixty-year cycle of twelve animal-named =
years groups.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mongol_calendar" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mongol calendar">Old Mongol calendar</a></b> us=
es the Mouse, the Ox, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leopard"=
 title=3D"Leopard">Leopard</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Hare" title=3D"Hare">Hare</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Crocodile" title=3D"Crocodile">Crocodile</a>, the Serpent, the Horse, th=
e Sheep, the Monkey, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hen_(bird=
)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hen (bird)">Hen</a>, the Dog and the Hog.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tibetan_calendar" ti=
tle=3D"Tibetan calendar">Tibetan calendar</a></b> replaces the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rooster_(zodiac)" title=3D"Rooster (zodiac)">R=
ooster</a> with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird" title=3D=
"Bird">bird</a>.
</p><p>The <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volga_Bulgars" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Volga Bulgars">Volga Bulgars</a></b>, <b><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kazars" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ka=
zars">Kazars</a></b> and other Turkic peoples replaced some animals by loca=
l fauna: Leopard (instead of Tiger), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Fish" title=3D"Fish">Fish</a> or Crocodile (instead of Dragon/Loong), <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hedgehog" title=3D"Hedgehog">Hedgeho=
g</a> (instead of Monkey), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asian_e=
lephant" title=3D"Asian elephant">Elephant</a> (instead of Pig), and <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camel" title=3D"Camel">Camel</a> (instea=
d of Rat/Mouse).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-46"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Persian_astrology=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Persian astrology">Persian</a></b> version=
 of the Eastern zodiac brought by Mongols during the Middle Ages, the Chine=
se word <i>l=C3=B3ng</i> and Mongol word <i>l=C5=AB</i> (Dragon) was transl=
ated as <i>nahang</i> meaning "water beast", and may refer to any dangerous=
 aquatic animal both mythical and real (crocodiles, hippos, sharks, sea ser=
pents, etc.). In the 20th century the term <i>nahang</i> is used almost exc=
lusively as meaning <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whale" title=
=3D"Whale">Whale</a>, thus switching the Loong for the Whale in the Persian=
 variant.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chines=
e_zodiac#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the traditional <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kazak=
hs" title=3D"Kazakhs">Kazakh</a></b> version of the twelve-year animal cycl=
e (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kazakh_language" title=3D"Kazak=
h language">Kazakh</a>: <span lang=3D"kk">=D0=BC=D2=AF=D1=88=D0=B5=D0=BB</s=
pan>, <i>m=C3=BC=C5=9Fel</i>), the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Dragon_(zodiac)" title=3D"Dragon (zodiac)">Dragon</a> is replaced by a sna=
il (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kazakh_language" title=3D"Kaza=
kh language">Kazakh</a>: <span lang=3D"kk">=D2=B1=D0=BB=D1=83</span>, <i>ul=
w</i>), and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tiger_(zodiac)" ti=
tle=3D"Tiger (zodiac)">Tiger</a> appears as a leopard (<a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kazakh_language" title=3D"Kazakh language">Kazakh</a>:=
 <span lang=3D"kk">=D0=B1=D0=B0=D1=80=D1=8B=D1=81</span>, <i>bar=C4=B1s</i>=
).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kyrgyz_people" ti=
tle=3D"Kyrgyz people">Kyrgyz</a></b> version of the Chinese zodiac (<a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kyrgyz_language" title=3D"Kyrgyz language=
">Kyrgyz</a>: <span lang=3D"ky">=D0=BC=D2=AF=D1=87=D3=A9=D0=BB</span>, <i>m=
=C3=BC=C3=A7=C3=B6l</i>) the words for the Dragon (<a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Kyrgyz_language" title=3D"Kyrgyz language">Kyrgyz</a>: <sp=
an lang=3D"ky">=D1=83=D0=BB=D1=83=D1=83</span>, <i>uluu</i>), Monkey (<a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kyrgyz_language" title=3D"Kyrgyz langua=
ge">Kyrgyz</a>: <span lang=3D"ky">=D0=BC=D0=B5=D1=87=D0=B8=D0=BD</span>, <i=
>me=C3=A7in</i>) and Tiger (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kyrgyz=
_language" title=3D"Kyrgyz language">Kyrgyz</a>: <span lang=3D"ky">=D0=B1=
=D0=B0=D1=80=D1=81</span>, <i>bars</i>) are only found in Chinese zodiac na=
mes, other animal names include Mouse, Cow, Rabbit, Snake, Horse, Sheep, Ch=
icken, Dog and Wild boar.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-51"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turkish_people" t=
itle=3D"Turkish people">Turkish</a></b> version of zodiac, the animals are =
almost the same, but it replaces Tiger with Leopard (<i>Pars</i>), Dragon w=
ith Fish (<i>Bal=C4=B1k</i>) and Goat with Sheep (<i>Koyun</i>). Remarkably=
, the practise of zodiac persisted since the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Ottoman_Empire" title=3D"Ottoman Empire">Ottoman Empire</a>, inc=
luding the presence of Pig (<i>Domuz</i>) despite contradicting Islamic rul=
e.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodiac#cite_note-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-53"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_zodia=
c#cite_note-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
