<p>Due to confusion with synonyms during translation, some of the animals d=
epicted by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_language" t=
itle=3D"English language">English</a> words did not exist in <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_China" title=3D"History of China">anc=
ient China</a>.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=
=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikip=
edia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"Th=
is claim needs references to reliable sources. (April 2021)">citation neede=
d</span></a></i>]</sup> For example:
</p>
<ul><li>The term <a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E9%BC%A0" class=
=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt:=E9=BC=A0">=E9=BC=A0</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Rat_(zodiac)" title=3D"Rat (zodiac)">Rat</a> can be transla=
ted as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mouse" title=3D"Mouse">Mous=
e</a>, as there are no distinctive words for the two <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Genus" title=3D"Genus">genera</a> in <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_language" title=3D"Chinese language">Chinese<=
/a>. However, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rat_(zodiac)" title=
=3D"Rat (zodiac)">Rat</a> is the most commonly used one among all the synon=
yms.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-spa=
ce:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation=
_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim need=
s references to reliable sources. (January 2022)">citation needed</span></a=
></i>]</sup></li>
<li>The term <a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%89%9B" class=3D"=
extiw" title=3D"wikt:=E7=89=9B">=E7=89=9B</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Ox_(zodiac)" title=3D"Ox (zodiac)">Ox</a>, a castrated <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bull" title=3D"Bull">Bull</a>, can be tra=
nslated interchangeably with other terms related to <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Cattle" title=3D"Cattle">Cattle</a> (male <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bull" title=3D"Bull">Bull</a>, female <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cow" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cow">Cow<=
/a>) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bubalus" title=3D"Bubalus=
">Buffalo</a>. However, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ox_(zodiac=
)" title=3D"Ox (zodiac)">Ox</a> is the most commonly used one among all the=
 synonyms.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"whi=
te-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Ci=
tation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This clai=
m needs references to reliable sources. (January 2022)">citation needed</sp=
an></a></i>]</sup></li>
<li>The term <a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%8D%AF" class=3D"=
extiw" title=3D"wikt:=E5=8D=AF">=E5=8D=AF</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Rabbit_(zodiac)" title=3D"Rabbit (zodiac)">Rabbit</a> can be tr=
anslated as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hare" title=3D"Hare">H=
are</a>, as =E5=8D=AF (and =E5=85=94) do not distinguish between the two ge=
nera of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leporids" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Leporids">leporids</a>. As hares are native to China and mos=
t of Asia and rabbits are not, this would be more accurate. However, in col=
loquial English <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rabbit#Differences=
_from_hares" title=3D"Rabbit"><i>Rabbit</i></a> can encompass hares as well=
.</li>
<li>The term <a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E8%9B%87" class=3D"=
extiw" title=3D"wikt:=E8=9B=87">=E8=9B=87</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Snake_(zodiac)" title=3D"Snake (zodiac)">Snake</a> can be trans=
lated as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Snake" title=3D"Snake">Se=
rpent</a>, which refers to a large species of snake and has the same behavi=
or, although this term is rarely used.</li>
<li>The term <a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%BE%8A" class=3D"=
extiw" title=3D"wikt:=E7=BE=8A">=E7=BE=8A</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Goat_(zodiac)" title=3D"Goat (zodiac)">Goat</a> can be translat=
ed interchangeably with other terms related to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Sheep" title=3D"Sheep">Sheep</a> (male <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Ram_(sheep)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ram (sheep)">=
Ram</a>, female Ewe). However, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goa=
t_(zodiac)" title=3D"Goat (zodiac)">Goat</a> is the most commonly used one =
among all the synonyms.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact"=
 style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=
=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (January 2022)">citati=
